		<li id="comment-3132">
<div class="clearfix"><div class="avatarholder"><img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/7e12e748480a919d5515be906d87ef8e?s=32&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ahousebythepark.com%2Fjournal%2Fwp-content%2Fthemes%2FHouse%2Fimages%2Fgravatar_default.gif%3Fs%3D32&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-32 photo' height='32' width='32' /></div>			<div class="commentauthor"><a href='http://www.paulmoment.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Paul Moment</a> says:</div></div>
			
			<p>One other quick note for those working with font tuning:  I&#8217;ve found the most success with making the fonts match up by using a combo of font-size and line-height.  The font-size seems to mostly be useful for IE, and the line-height in conjuntion with font-size seems to work great for Mozilla, etc.  Also, setting the line-height just slightly higher than the font-size (I use pixels, so it&#8217;s generally the font-size + 2px) seems to even everything out nicely.  So in your sIFR CSS style it would look like:</p>
<p>.sIFR-hasFlash h1<br />
{<br />
	visibility:hidden;<br />
	font-size:14px;<br />
	line-height:16px;<br />
}</p>
<p>Letter-spacing hasn&#8217;t really worked at all for me for whatever reason&#8230; Hope that&#8217;s helpful to someone.</p>

			<div class="commentmetadata"><a href="#comment-3132" title="">#110</a> - March 18th, 2005 at 9:06 pm </div>


