		<li id="comment-3224">
<div class="clearfix"><div class="avatarholder"><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/ad418e3e53e0ba71ba56b7df978671e8?s=32&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ahousebythepark.com%2Fjournal%2Fwp-content%2Fthemes%2FHouse%2Fimages%2Fgravatar_default.gif%3Fs%3D32&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-32 photo' height='32' width='32' /></div>			<div class="commentauthor"><a href='http://novemberborn.net/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Mark Wubben</a> says:</div></div>
			
			<p>Roberto, in a perfect world even the generated code would be valid. Unfortunately we don&#8217;t live in such a world, and the way sIFR works now is the only way it can work. Furthermore I think there is a difference between the markup of a page and what happens to the Document Object Model which represents that page. sIFR modifies the DOM, not the HTML.</p>
<p>Also, the test case you pointed to validates as HTML 4.01 Strict.</p>

			<div class="commentmetadata"><a href="#comment-3224" title="">#202</a> - April 17th, 2005 at 4:07 am </div>


