		<li id="comment-3263" class="alt">
<div class="clearfix"><div class="avatarholder"><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/c4e48fb1980b1ae0382e1519b029faa1?s=32&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ahousebythepark.com%2Fjournal%2Fwp-content%2Fthemes%2FHouse%2Fimages%2Fgravatar_default.gif%3Fs%3D32&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-32 photo' height='32' width='32' /></div>			<div class="commentauthor"><a href='http://www.jor-on.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Jordi Romkema</a> says:</div></div>
			
			<p>For a project I&#8217;m working on I needed to capitalize each word (ala text-transform: capitalize in CSS). I couldn&#8217;t find this feature within sIFR (there&#8217;s only sCase: upper &#038; lower) so I made my own. This might be cool as a new feature and if not, it might be useful to others who read this page.</p>
<p>You can use it by entering &#8216;capitalize&#8217; as the value for sCase instead of &#8216;upper&#8217; or &#8216;lower&#8217;.</p>
<p>In sifr.js I added this function:</p>
<p>function capitalize(s) {<br />
s = s.toLowerCase();<br />
	if (s.length > 0) {<br />
		for (i = 0; i </p>
<p>And also in sifr.js I added this:</p>
<p>case &#8220;capitalize&#8221;:<br />
						sContent += capitalize(sValue);<br />
						break;</p>
<p>after:</p>
<p>case &#8220;upper&#8221;:<br />
						sContent += sValue.toUpperCase();<br />
						break;</p>
<p>It&#8217;s working for me, please let me know your thoughts :)</p>

			<div class="commentmetadata"><a href="#comment-3263" title="">#241</a> - April 27th, 2005 at 12:43 pm </div>


		</li>

	
	
