qzvlpco1_500.jpg' alt='' width='240' height='320' /></div><div class="autodiv_double"><p><a href="http://dutchuncleagency.blogspot.com/2010/09/noma-bar-ibm-campaign.html">Great illustrations from Noma Bar for IBM’s new “Outcomes” campaign</a>. This is why — as a ho-hum digital designer — I don’t call myself an actual artist. (via <a href="http://cameronmoll.tumblr.com/post/1222933862/ibm-outcomes-campaign">cameron</a>)</p></div></div><div><a href="http://www.mikeindustries.com/blog/archive/2010/10/great-illustrations-from-noma-bar-for-ibm-s-new" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to this entry" class="noborder"><img src="http://www.mikeindustries.com/wp/wp-content/themes/Mike-Industries-Two/images/icon_comment_medium.gif" width="10" height="10" alt="" class="comment_icon" /></a><a href="http://www.mikeindustries.com/blog/archive/2010/10/great-illustrations-from-noma-bar-for-ibm-s-new" title="Leave a comment">3</a></div></div></div><div class="post" id="post-5496"><div class="post_content"><div class="entry"><div class="autodiv"><a href="http://ma.tt/2010/09/email-load/">Email Load Indicator</a>: <p>I love Matt’s dynamic email load indicator. I’ve always wanted this feature to somehow exist in mail clients… so for example, as soon as you put my mail in the “To:” field of an email, you can hover over it and see my current queue length or whatever.</p>
